# Chttrix Collaboration Platform — Architecture Audit Report

**Date:** March 12, 2026  
**Auditor Role:** Principal Software Architect  
**Scope:** Pre-restructuring system analysis  
**Audience:** Engineering leadership, platform team

---

## 1. Repository Structure Overview

The repository is a **monorepo** with two primary applications sharing a single Git history. There is no dedicated workspace tooling (Nx, Turborepo, Lerna); the root [package.json](file:///Users/thrishankkuntimaddi/Documents/Chttrix/ChttrixCollab/package.json) coordinates a simple concurrent-dev startup.

```
ChttrixCollab/
├── client/               React + Vite web application
│   └── src/
│       ├── components/   Feature UI components (deeply nested by domain)
│       ├── contexts/     React context providers (global state)
│       ├── hooks/        Custom reusable hooks
│       ├── modules/      Experimental modular decomposition (chat module)
│       ├── pages/        Route-level page components
│       ├── services/     API service layer (axios wrappers)
│       ├── shared/       Design-system primitives (Avatar, Button, Modal, etc.)
│       └── utils/        Low-level utilities (crypto, token, deviceId, logger)
│
├── server/               Node.js + Express backend
│   ├── server.js         Single monolithic entrypoint (819 lines)
│   ├── socket/index.js   Socket.IO event handler (775 lines)
│   ├── middleware/        Auth, permissions, validation
│   ├── models/           Legacy Mongoose models (flat)
│   ├── routes/           V1→V2 compatibility proxy
│   └── src/
│       ├── features/     Domain-driven feature modules (controller/routes/service)
│       ├── modules/      Cross-cutting technical modules (messages, encryption, threads)
│       ├── models/       V2 Mongoose models
│       ├── shared/       Shared utilities (rooms, OTP, upload)
│       └── socket/       Socket sub-handlers (huddles)
│
├── expansion/            Scratch/planning directory
└── studies/              Research notes
```

### Key Architectural Patterns

| Pattern | Location | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Domain-driven features | `server/src/features/` | controller + routes + service per domain |
| Context-based global state | `client/src/contexts/` | 13 context providers |
| Service-layer API abstraction | `client/src/services/` | thin wrappers around axios |
| Dual-model architecture | `server/models/` (legacy) + `server/src/models/` (V2) | migration in progress |
| V1→V2 route proxy | `server/routes/v1-to-v2-proxy.js` | backwards-compat shim |

---

## 2. Web Client Architecture

### 2.1 Folder Structure

The React application uses a **feature-domain component organization**, grouped under `src/components/` by functional area (`messagesComp`, `tasksComp`, `admin`, `manager`, `company`, `layout`, etc.). Pages are in `src/pages/` mirroring the same domain groupings. There is a nascent `src/modules/chat/` directory attempting a stricter modular decomposition — a prototype of the desired future architecture.

### 2.2 State Management

State management is **entirely React Context API** — no Redux or Zustand in use.

| Context | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| `AuthContext` | User identity, access/refresh tokens, encryption-ready state |
| `SocketContext` | Socket.IO instance, event listener registry |
| `WorkspaceContext` | Active workspace state |
| `HuddleContext` | Huddle/meeting session state |
| `NotesContext` | Notes data |
| `TasksContext` | Task data |
| `CompanyContext` | Company-wide data |
| `DepartmentContext` | Department data |
| `ContactsContext` | Contact book |
| `NotificationsContext` | In-app notification feed |
| `ThemeContext` | Light/dark theme |
| `ToastContext` | App-wide toast notifications |
| `BlogsContext` | Blog/update feed |

**Observation:** 13 contexts create a deeply nested provider tree in `App.js`. Without memoization discipline, re-renders cascade across the tree. This is the primary maintainability risk on the client side.

### 2.3 API Communication Layer

**Primary client:** `src/services/api.js`  
- Axios instance with `baseURL = VITE_BACKEND_URL || 'http://localhost:8080'`
- **Request interceptor:** Attaches `Authorization: Bearer <accessToken>` from `localStorage`
- **Response interceptor:** Handles 401 → silent token refresh → retry queue; dispatches `auth:force-logout` custom event on failure; also reads `x-access-token` header for inline server-side refresh

**Secondary client:** `src/utils/apiClient.js`  
- Native `fetch` wrapper for device-tracked calls
- Attaches `X-Device-ID` header alongside the bearer token
- Handles `403 DEVICE_REVOKED` responses

**Domain service files** (26 services in `src/services/`) wrap the axios instance with domain-specific calls. `api.js` is the single axios instance that almost all services import — a good pattern.

### 2.4 Socket Communication

**Entry point:** `src/contexts/SocketContext.jsx`

Architecture:
- Socket is created with `autoConnect: false` on user login/load, then connected explicitly after encryption initialization completes (Phase 1 isolation)
- Reconnection logic built-in: 5 attempts, 1s delay, 10s timeout
- On `connect_error` due to authentication failure, the socket context itself retries the token refresh before reconnecting
- A **fan-out listener registry pattern** is used: `SocketContext` subscribes to all socket events centrally and dispatches them to registered listener callbacks via `useRef` arrays (`channelListenersRef`, `messageListenersRef`, etc.)

**Socket event categories:**
- Channel events: `channel-created/updated/deleted`, `invited-to-channel`, `removed-from-channel`, `admin-assigned/demoted`, etc.
- Message events: `new-message`, `new-dm-session`, `message-deleted/pinned/unpinned`, `read-update`, `reaction-added/removed`, `reconnected`
- Workspace events: `workspace-joined/created/updated/deleted`
- Task events: `task-created/updated/deleted/assigned/removed`
- Note events: `note-created/updated/deleted/shared`
- Update events: `company:update:created/deleted/reacted`
- Notification events: `notification:new`

**Key files:** `src/hooks/useChatSocket.js`, `src/hooks/useConversation.js`, `src/modules/chat/hooks/useRealtimeEvents.js`

### 2.5 Authentication Flow

```
Login (email/password)
  → POST /api/auth/login → {accessToken, refreshToken, user}
  → Store accessToken in localStorage, refreshToken in localStorage
  → Initialize encryption (Phase 1 identity keys via identityKeyService)
  → SocketContext creates socket instance, waits for connectSocket() call
  → AuthContext runs auto-repair of conversation keys (fire-and-forget)
  → Token auto-refresh setInterval every 10 minutes
  
Page Reload / App Start
  → AuthContext.loadUser() tries localStorage token → /api/auth/me
  → If 401: silentRefresh() via httpOnly cookie + body refresh token
  → On success: restore user state + re-initialize encryption
  
OAuth (Google)
  → OAuthSuccess.jsx handles redirect token exchange
  → OAuthPasswordSetup.jsx for first-time OAuth users
```

**Token storage:** Access token in `localStorage`; refresh token in both `localStorage` (body fallback for cross-origin) and `httpOnly` cookie (primary).

### 2.6 Encryption Usage

End-to-end encryption is a **substantial, first-class subsystem** with its own lifecycle:

**Key Hierarchy:**
```
User Password
  → PBKDF2-SHA256 (100,000 iterations, 16-byte salt)
  → UMEK (User Master Encryption Key, AES-256-GCM)
    → Encrypts Identity Private Key (stored on server as encrypted blob)
      → Identity Key Pair (ECDH or ECDSA for key exchange)
        → Conversation Keys (per-channel/DM, AES-256-GCM)
          → Thread Keys (derived via HKDF from conversation key + parentMessageId)
            → Message encryption/decryption
```

**Key files:**
- `src/utils/crypto.js` — Core Web Crypto API primitives (AES-GCM, PBKDF2, HKDF, encoding)
- `src/utils/cryptoIdentity.js` — Identity key pair management
- `src/utils/encryptionUtils.js` — High-level encryption helpers
- `src/services/identityKeyService.js` — Identity key initialization and recovery
- `src/services/conversationKeyService.js` — Per-conversation key management
- `src/services/messageEncryptionService.js` — Message-level encrypt/decrypt
- `src/services/keyManagement.js` — Key storage and retrieval (IndexedDB via internal service)
- `src/services/clientKeyDistribution.js` — Distributes keys to new members

**Client-server E2EE interaction:** The server holds encrypted blobs (never plaintext keys); the server's `SERVER_KEK` (AES-256 server key encryption key) is used only to re-wrap workspace keys, not to decrypt messages.

### 2.7 AI Integration Points

- **`src/components/ai/ChttrixAIChat/ChttrixAIChat.jsx`** — Chat UI panel
- **`src/services/aiService.js`** — Client-side service calls `/api/ai/chat`, `/api/ai/summarize`, `/api/ai/generate-task`
- **Notes module** — `src/pages/SidebarComp/notesComponents/ui/AIPanel.jsx` provides AI assistance within note editing

The AI integration is currently **stateless and request-driven** (no streaming). Conversation history is passed with each request from the client.

