## 3. Backend Architecture

### 3.1 Routing Architecture

**Entrypoint:** `server/server.js` (819 lines)

The server registers **40+ route mounts** directly in `server.js`. The routing follows two generations:

**Legacy (V1) routes** — flat mount at `/api/`:
```
/api/auth, /api/admin, /api/channels, /api/polls, /api/chat,
/api/workspaces, /api/users, /api/notes, /api/tasks, /api/dashboard, etc.
```

**Modular (V2) routes** — clean domain-driven mount at `/api/v2/`:
```
/api/v2/messages, /api/v2/dm, /api/v2/encryption, /api/v2/identity,
/api/v2/conversations, /api/v2/crypto, /api/v2/devices, /api/v2/security,
/api/v2/tasks, /api/v2/notes, /api/v2/favorites, /api/v2/status,
/api/v2/admin, /api/v2/audit, /api/v2/uploads, /api/v2/link-preview
```

A **V1→V2 compatibility proxy** (`routes/v1-to-v2-proxy.js`) exists for backward compatibility during migration.

**Inline routes in server.js:** `GET/POST/PATCH/DELETE /api/scheduled-meetings` — not yet moved to a feature module.

### 3.2 Service Layer

`server/src/features/` follows a consistent pattern:

```
features/<domain>/
  ├── <domain>.routes.js       Express router
  ├── <domain>.controller.js   Request/response handlers
  ├── <domain>.service.js      Business logic
  ├── <domain>.model.js        (if co-located; otherwise in /models/)
  └── <domain>.validator.js    Input validation
```

Notable domains: `auth`, `channels`, `chat`, `company`, `company-registration`, `company-updates`, `company-analytics`, `crypto`, `departments`, `devices`, `employees`, `favorites`, `integration`, `notes`, `notifications`, `onboarding`, `people`, `polls`, `search`, `security`, `tasks`, `updates`, `users`, `workspaces`, `managers`, `admin`, `analytics`, `audit`, `ai`, `status`, `support`.

### 3.3 Middleware Structure

| Middleware | File | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `requireAuth` | `middleware/auth.js` | JWT verification + silent refresh via cookie |
| `requireOwner` | `middleware/permissionMiddleware.js` | Owner-role gate |
| `requireAdmin` | `middleware/permissionMiddleware.js` | Admin-role gate |
| `requireManager` | `middleware/permissionMiddleware.js` | Manager-role gate |
| `sanitizeInput` | `middleware/validate.js` | MongoDB injection prevention ($-operator stripping) |
| `passport.initialize()` | `config/passport.js` | Google OAuth |
| `helmet()` | inline | Security headers |
| `cors()` | inline | Origin whitelist |
| `rateLimit()` | inline | Auth endpoint protection (20 req/min production) |
| `refreshLimiter` | inline | Dedicated `/refresh` rate limiter (60 req/min) |

Mount-level middleware is applied at the router mount for defence-in-depth (e.g., `requireAdmin` at `/api/admin-dashboard` mount level in addition to per-route guards).

### 3.4 Authentication Flow (Backend)

```
POST /api/auth/login
  → Validates credentials
  → Signs accessToken (JWT, 15min, ACCESS_TOKEN_SECRET)
  → Signs refreshToken (JWT, rotated, REFRESH_TOKEN_SECRET)
  → Stores refresh token hash in User.refreshTokens[] array
  → Sets httpOnly cookie "jwt" + returns tokens in body

middleware/auth.js (per request)
  → Reads Bearer token from Authorization header
  → Verifies with ACCESS_TOKEN_SECRET
  → If TokenExpiredError: falls through to refresh cookie path
  → If refresh cookie valid: auto-issues new accessToken
  → Sets x-access-token response header for client pickup
  → Attaches decoded payload to req.user

Socket.IO middleware (server.js)
  → Reads token from socket.handshake.auth.token
  → Verifies JWT, attaches socket.user = { id: decoded.sub }
  → Rejects with "Authentication failed" on any error
```

### 3.5 Socket Server Implementation

**Configuration:** Socket.IO server attached to the HTTP server with optional Redis adapter (enabled when `REDIS_URL` environment variable is set — supports horizontal scaling).

**`server/socket/index.js`** (775 lines) — primary handler `registerChatHandlers(io, socket)`:

**Room naming convention:**
```
user:<userId>           — personal targeted events (notifications)
user_<userId>           — personal targeted events (messages/DMs) [inconsistent]
channel:<channelId>     — channel broadcast
dm:<dmSessionId>        — DM broadcast
workspace:<workspaceId> — workspace-wide events
company_<companyId>     — company-wide events
company:updates:<id>    — company updates feed
platform-admins         — chttrix admin targeting
user-support:<id>       — support DM targeting
```

> ⚠️ **Room naming inconsistency noted:** Two parallel patterns exist — `user:X` (colon) and `user_X` (underscore). This is a known technical debt from the channel system KI.

**Event handlers registered:** `join-dm`, `join-channel`, `chat:join`, `join-workspace`, `join-company-updates`, `send-message`, `mark-chat-read`, `message-read`, `typing`, `add-reaction`, `remove-reaction`, `delete-message`, `pin-message`, `unpin-message`, `disconnect`

**Session restoration on reconnect:** On every connection, the server auto-rejoins the user to all their DM and channel rooms by querying the database, then emits `reconnected` to sync the client.

**Huddle handler:** `src/socket/handlers/huddles.socket.js` is registered separately via `registerHuddleHandlers(io, socket)`.

### 3.6 Encryption Logic (Backend)

**Server-side E2EE infrastructure:**
- `server/src/modules/encryption/` — E2EE route handlers
- `server/src/modules/conversations/` — Conversation key management, repair, crypto utilities
  - `conversationKeys.service.js` — Key storage and retrieval
  - `conversationKeys.crypto.js` — Key wrapping/unwrapping
  - `serverKEK.crypto.js` — Server Key Encryption Key operations (AES-256, re-wrapping only)
  - `cryptoUtils.js` — Shared crypto helpers
- `server/src/modules/identity/` — User identity public key registry
- `server/src/features/crypto/identity.controller.js` — UMEK-based recovery endpoints
- `server/models/ConversationKey.js`, `UserIdentityKey.js`, `encryption.js` — Key storage models
- `server/migrations/add-e2ee-support.js` — Schema migration for E2EE fields

**Server role:** The server is a **key distribution server, not a decryption server**. It stores encrypted blobs (private keys wrapped in UMEK, conversation keys wrapped per-user). It never has access to plaintext keys or messages.

### 3.7 AI Service Integration

**Controller:** `server/src/features/ai/ai.controller.js`

- Uses `@google/generative-ai` SDK with **Gemini 2.0 Flash Exp** model
- Implements **function calling** (tool use): the AI can invoke `send_message_to_channel`, `send_message_to_all_general_channels`, `get_user_channels`, `create_task`, `get_current_workspace`
- Three endpoints: `chat`, `summarize`, `generateTask`
- AI actions execute server-side, giving Gemini real write access to the platform (send messages, create tasks)
- Auth is enforced: `req.user.sub` is passed to all AI action executors

